        this.driver = driver;
    }

    //&#128071;
    public void setTimestamp(Map&lt;String, String&gt; timeStamp) {
        this.timestamp= timestamp;
    }

    //&#128071;
    public Map&lt;String, String&gt; getTimestamp() {
        return timestamp;
    }
}
```

When you create an object of the class, simply pass `ServerValue.TIMESTAMP` as the third parameter to the constructor. One thing to mention is that the `ServerValue.TIMESTAMP` is just a token that the Realtime Database converts to a number on the server. The timestamp will only appear in the database after the write operation completes. So you also might consider attaching a complete listener to see when the operation completes.

However, if you already have added the data into the database, and you only want to perform an update, then the following lines of code are required:

```
Map map = new HashMap();
map.put(&quot;timestamp&quot;, ServerValue.TIMESTAMP);
ref.child(&quot;yourNode&quot;).updateChildren(map);
```

